<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-02-08T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-02-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="477" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d477">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">882.73/20: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bundy</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-02-08T17:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">February
                                            8, 1919, 5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>Legation[’s] February 4, 11 a.m.</p>
                            <p>Department would be willing to recommend for appointment by Liberian
                                Government technical expert to supervise plant and staff in case
                                Liberia becomes solely dependent upon German wireless plant for
                                communication.</p>
                            <p>The American Mission at Paris has been advised of each step in the
                                German cable controversy with request to keep the Liberian Mission
                                advised.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>